solution:
If the incident neutrons striking the crystal produce diffraction, then the incident wavelength is also approximately \(10^{-10} \mathrm{~m}\). Therefore, the energy of the incident neutrons is

\[
\begin{aligned}
E & = \frac{p^{2}}{2 m_{\mathrm{n}}} = \frac{\left(\frac{h}{\lambda}\right)^{2}}{2 m_{\mathrm{n}}} = \frac{h^{2}}{2 m_{\mathrm{n}} \lambda^{2}} = \left(\frac{h c}{\lambda}\right)^{2} \cdot \frac{1}{m_{\mathrm{n}} c^{2}} \\
& = \left(\frac{4.1358 \times 10^{-15} \times 3 \times 10^{8}}{1 \times 10^{-10}}\right)^{2} \cdot \frac{1}{939 \times 10^{6} \, \mathrm{eV}} \\
& = 8.2 \times 10^{-2} \, \mathrm{(eV)}
\end{aligned}
\]

The concentration of free electrons in copper is
\[
n=\frac{8.9 \times 10^3}{63.5} \times 6.02 \times 10^{23}=8.4 \times 10^{28} \, \mathrm{m}^{-3}
\]

The Fermi energy is
\[
\begin{aligned}
E_{\mathrm{F}}^{0} & =\frac{\hbar^2}{2m} \left(3\pi^{2}n\right)^{\frac{2}{3}} =\frac{\left(1.055 \times 10^{-34}\right)^{2}}{2 \times 9.1 \times 10^{-31}} \times \left(3\pi^{2} \times 8.4 \times 10^{28}\right)^{\frac{2}{3}} \\
& =1.12 \times 10^{-18} \, \mathrm{J} = \frac{1.12 \times 10^{-18}}{1.6 \times 10^{-19}} = 7.01 \, \mathrm{eV}
\end{aligned}
\]

The effective mass of the electron:
\[
\begin{aligned}
m_{\mathrm{e}}^{*} = \frac{\hbar^{2}}{\frac{\mathrm{d}^{2} E(k)}{\mathrm{d} k^{2}}} = \frac{\hbar^{2}}{\left(-\frac{6 \hbar^{2}}{m}\right)} = -\frac{m}{6} = -\frac{9.11 \times 10^{-31}}{6} = -1.52 \times 10^{-31} \, \mathrm{kg}
\end{aligned}
\]
The effective mass of the hole:
\[
m_{\mathrm{h}}^{*} = -m_{\mathrm{e}}^{*} = 1.52 \times 10^{-31} \, \mathrm{kg} = 0.17 m_{0}
\]

Since \(\boldsymbol{q}_{3} = 2.22 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{i} + 0.92 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{j}\) exceeds the limit of the first Brillouin zone \(1.57 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1}\), we use periodic boundary conditions:

Choose the reciprocal lattice vector \(\boldsymbol{G}_{h} = -\boldsymbol{b}_{1} = -3.14 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{i}\), then

\[
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{q}_{3} & =\boldsymbol{q}_{1}+\boldsymbol{q}_{2}+\boldsymbol{G}_{h}=2.22 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{i}+0.92 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{j}-3.14 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{i} \\
& =-0.92 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{i}+0.92 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{j} \\
& =-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \times 1.3 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{i}+\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \times 1.3 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{j}
\end{aligned}
\]

The adjusted phonon wave vector is along the \([\overline{1}, 1, 0]\) direction, with magnitude still \(1.3 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1}\), which is within the first Brillouin zone.

\[
\begin{aligned}
P_{R} \Psi_{k}^{x}(\boldsymbol{r}) &= \Psi_{k}^{x}\left(\boldsymbol{r}^{\prime}\right) \\
&= c \sum_{n} \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{0} X_{n}} \phi_{p x}\left(x^{\prime}-X_{n}, y^{\prime}-Y_{n}, z^{\prime}-Z_{n}\right) \\
&= c \sum_{n} \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{0} X_{n}} \phi_{p x}\left(y-X_{n}, -x-Y_{n}, z-Z_{n}\right) \\
&= c \sum_{n} \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{0} X_{n}} \left(y-X_{n}\right) f\left(\sqrt{\left(y-X_{n}\right)^{2}+\left(-x-Y_{n}\right)^{2}+\left(z-Z_{n}\right)^{2}}\right) \\
&= c \sum_{n} \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{0} X_{n}} \left(y-X_{n}\right) f\left(\sqrt{\left(x+Y_{n}\right)^{2}+\left(y-X_{n}\right)^{2}+\left(z-Z_{n}\right)^{2}}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
\begin{aligned}
&= c \sum_{n^{\prime}} \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} \boldsymbol{r}^{\prime} \cdot \boldsymbol{R}_{n^{\prime}}} \phi_{p y}\left(\boldsymbol{r}-\boldsymbol{R}_{n^{\prime}}\right) \\
&= \Psi_{k}^{y}(\boldsymbol{r})
\end{aligned}
\]

Where:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{k}^{\prime} &= \left(0, k_{0}, 0\right) \\
\boldsymbol{R}_{n^{\prime}} &= -Y_{n} \boldsymbol{i} + X_{n} \boldsymbol{j} + Z_{n} \boldsymbol{k}
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus, the transformation results in another Bloch wave, but the wave vector changes to \(\boldsymbol{k}^{\prime}=\left(0, k_{0}, 0\right)\), which is a Bloch wave in the \(y\) direction.

Assuming boron atoms occupy substitutional positions, calculate the crystal density using the following formula:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\rho_{\mathrm{s}}^{n} & =\frac{797488 \times \frac{28.086 \times 10^{-3}}{6.022 \times 10^{23}}+2512 \times \frac{10.811 \times 10^{-3}}{6.022 \times 10^{23}}}{1 \times 10^{5} \times\left(5.4249 \times 10^{-10}\right)^{3}} \\
& =\frac{797488 \times 28.086 \times 10^{-3}+2512 \times 10.811 \times 10^{-3}}{1 \times 10^{5} \times\left(5.4249 \times 10^{-10}\right)^{3} \times 6.022 \times 10^{23}} \\
& =\frac{22398.24797+27.157}{159.6523116 \times 6.022 \times 10^{-2}} = 2.33251 \times 10^{3} \mathrm{~kg} \cdot \mathrm{m}^{-3}
\end{aligned}
\]

Assuming boron occupies interstitial positions, calculate the overall density of the unit cell using the following formula:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\rho_{i}^{*} & = \frac{M}{V} \\
& = \frac{8 \times 10^{5} \times \frac{28.086 \times 10^{-3}}{6.022 \times 10^{23}} + 2512 \times \frac{10.811 \times 10^{-3}}{6.022 \times 10^{23}}}{1 \times 10^{5} \times \left(5.4249 \times 10^{-10}\right)^{3}} \\
& = \frac{8 \times 10^{5} \times 28.086 \times 10^{-3} + 2512 \times 10.811 \times 10^{-3}}{10^{5} \times \left(5.4249 \times 10^{-10}\right)^{3} \times 6.022 \times 10^{23}}
\end{aligned}
\]

The calculation yields: \(\rho_{i}^{*} = 2.33985 \times 10^{3} \, \text{kg} \cdot \text{m}^{-3}\).

First, apply integration by parts to solve \(I_{1}\)

\[
\begin{aligned}
I_{1} & =-\frac{a_{0}}{2}\left[\left.\left(\sin G r \mathrm{e}^{-\frac{2 r}{a_{0}}}\right)\right|_{0}^{\infty}-\int_{0}^{\infty} G \cos G r \mathrm{e}^{-\frac{2 r}{a_{0}}} \mathrm{d} r\right] \\
& =\frac{G a_{0}}{2} \int_{0}^{\infty} \cos G r \mathrm{e}^{-\frac{2 r}{a_{0}}} \mathrm{d} r=-\frac{G a_{0}^{2}}{4}\left[\left.\left(\cos G r \mathrm{e}^{-\frac{2 r}{a_{0}}}\right)\right|_{0}^{\infty}+\int_{0}^{\infty} G \sin G r \mathrm{e}^{-\frac{2 r}{a_{0}}} \mathrm{d} r\right] \\
& =\frac{G a_{0}^{2}}{4}-\frac{G^{2} a_{0}^{2}}{4} I_{1}
\end{aligned}
\]

Rearranging yields

\[
I_{1}=\frac{G a_{0}^{2}}{4+a_{0}^{2} G^{2}}
\]

By similar calculations, we find

\[
I_{2}=\frac{2 a_{0}}{4+a_{0}^{2} G^{2}}
\]

Condition for extremum:
\[
\frac{\mathrm{d} E(k)}{\mathrm{d} k} = -\frac{6 \hbar^{2}}{m} k = 0
\]
The top of the full band is at \(k=0\), and the energy of the electron at the top of the full band is:
\[
\begin{aligned}
E(k=0) &= \frac{\hbar^{2} k_{1}^{2}}{6 m} = \frac{\left(1.055 \times 10^{-34}\right)^{2} \times \left(3.98 \times 10^{8}\right)^{2}}{6 \times 9.11 \times 10^{-31}} \\
&= 3.195 \times 10^{-22} \, \mathrm{J} = 1.994 \times 10^{-3} \, \mathrm{eV}
\end{aligned}
\]
The energy of the hole at \(k_{1}\) is:
\[
\begin{aligned}
E_{\mathrm{h}} &= -E\left(k_{1}\right) = -\left(\frac{\hbar^{2} k_{1}^{2}}{6 m} - \frac{3 \hbar^{2} k_{1}^{2}}{m}\right) = \frac{17 \hbar^{2} k_{1}^{2}}{6 m} \\
&= \frac{17 \times \left(1.055 \times 10^{-34}\right)^{2} \times \left(3.98 \times 10^{8}\right)^{2}}{6 \times 9.11 \times 10^{-31}} \\
&= 5.489 \times 10^{-21} \, \mathrm{J} = 0.034 \, \mathrm{eV}
\end{aligned}
\]

First, calculate the average interaction energy \(u\) between an atom and its six nearest neighbor atoms. Given the assumption that metal atoms \(A\) and \(B\) are randomly and uniformly distributed over all positions, on average, each lattice site in the binary alloy has \(A\) atoms and \(B\) atoms as nearest neighbors in the ratios \(\frac{N_{A}}{N}\) and \(\frac{N_{B}}{N}\) respectively. Likewise, the probability for the occurrence of atoms \(A\) and \(B\) themselves at any given site is \(\frac{N_{A}}{N}\) and \(\frac{N_{B}}{N}\) respectively. Therefore, the average interaction energy between an atom and its nearest neighbors is:
\[
\begin{aligned}
u & =6\left[(-J) \frac{N_{A}}{N}+J \frac{N_{B}}{N}\right] \frac{N_{A}}{N}+6\left[(-J) \frac{N_{B}}{N}+J \frac{N_{A}}{N}\right] \frac{N_{B}}{N} \\
& =6\left[(-J) \frac{N_{A}^{2}+N_{B}^{2}}{N^{2}}+J \frac{2 N_{A} N_{B}}{N^{2}}\right]=-\frac{6 J}{N^{2}}\left(N_{A}-N_{B}\right)^{2}
\end{aligned}
\]
Thus, the total interaction energy of the binary alloy composed of \(N_{A}\) metal atoms \(A\) and \(N_{B}\) metal atoms \(B\) is:
\[
U=\frac{N}{2} u=-\frac{3 J}{N}\left(N_{A}-N_{B}\right)^{2}=-3 N J x^{2}
\]

The electron concentration in silver is \(n = \frac{10.5}{107.87} \times 6.022 \times 10^{23} = 5.86 \times 10^{22} \ \mathrm{cm}^{-3}\).

Fermi energy \(E_{\mathrm{F}}\) and Fermi temperature \(T_{\mathrm{F}}\):

\[
\begin{aligned}
E_{\mathrm{F}} & = \frac{\hbar^{2}}{2 m}\left(3 \pi^{2} n\right)^{\frac{2}{3}} = \frac{\left(1.05 \times 10^{-34}\right)^{2}}{2 \times 9.1 \times 10^{-31}} \times \left(3 \times 3.14^{2} \times 5.86 \times 10^{22}\right)^{\frac{2}{3}} \\
& = 8.747 \times 10^{-19} \ \mathrm{J} = 5.46 \ \mathrm{eV} \\
T_{\mathrm{F}} & = \frac{E_{\mathrm{F}}}{k_{\mathrm{B}}} = \frac{5.46 \ \mathrm{eV}}{8.617 \times 10^{-5} \ \mathrm{eV/K}} = 6.34 \times 10^{4} \ \mathrm{K}
\end{aligned}
\]

In the free electron gas model, the size of the Fermi sphere is determined by the electron density in the metal, whose Fermi wave vector is

\[
k_{\mathrm{F}} = \left(3 n \pi^{2}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}}
\]

Metallic potassium has a body-centered cubic structure with a volume of \(a^3\), containing 2 electrons per unit cell, therefore \(n = \frac{2}{a^3}\). Thus,

\[
\begin{aligned}
k_{\mathrm{F}} & = \left(3 n \pi^{2}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}} = \left(3 \times \frac{2}{a^{3}} \pi^{2}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}} = \left(\frac{6\pi^{2}}{a^3}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}} \\
& = 1.240 \times \frac{3.14}{5.333 \times 10^{-10}} = 7.31 \times 10^{9} \ (\mathrm{m}^{-1})
\end{aligned}
\]

Also,

\[
E_{\mathrm{F}}^{0} = \frac{\hbar^{2} k_{\mathrm{F}}^{2}}{2 m^{*}} = k_{\mathrm{B}} T_{\mathrm{F}}
\]

Therefore,

\[
\begin{aligned}
m^{*} & = \frac{\hbar^{2} k_{\mathrm{F}}^{2}}{2 k_{\mathrm{B}} T_{\mathrm{F}}} = \frac{\left(1.055 \times 10^{-34}\right)^{2} \times \left(7.31 \times 10^{9}\right)^{2}}{2 \times 1.38 \times 10^{-23} \times 1.97 \times 10^{4}} \\
& = 1.0939 \times 10^{-30} = 1.2 m_{0}
\end{aligned}
\]

where \(m_{0}\) is the rest mass of the electron.

Assume the phonon wavelength is \(\lambda^{\prime}\)

\[
\frac{1}{\lambda^{\prime}}=|\boldsymbol{q}|=2\left|\boldsymbol{k}_{0}\right| \sin \frac{\theta}{2}=2 \frac{1}{\lambda_{0}} \sin \frac{\theta}{2}
\]

where \(\lambda_{0}\) is the wavelength of the incident light, and the corresponding angular frequency of the phonon \(\omega^{\prime}\) is

\[
\omega^{\prime}=2 \pi f^{\prime}=\frac{2 \pi}{\lambda^{\prime}} v=4 \pi v \sin \frac{\theta}{2} \frac{1}{\lambda_{0}}
\]

Similarly, the angular frequencies corresponding to the photons with wave vectors \(\boldsymbol{k}_{0}\) and \(\boldsymbol{k}\) are

\[
\begin{aligned}
\omega_{0} & =2 \pi f_{0}=\frac{2 \pi}{\lambda_{0}} \frac{c}{n} \\
\omega & =2 \pi f=\frac{2 \pi}{\lambda} \frac{c}{n}
\end{aligned}
\]

The interaction between photons and phonons follows the law of energy conservation,

\[
\hbar \omega-\hbar \omega_{0}= \pm \hbar \omega^{\prime}
\]

Substituting equations (1), (2), and (3) into the above equation

\[
\begin{gathered}
\hbar \frac{2 \pi}{\lambda} \frac{c}{n}-\hbar \frac{2 \pi}{\lambda_{0}} \frac{c}{n}= \pm \hbar \cdot 4 \pi v \sin \frac{\theta}{2} \frac{1}{\lambda_{0}} \\
\frac{1}{\lambda}-\frac{1}{\lambda_{0}}= \pm \frac{2 n v}{c} \frac{1}{\lambda_{0}} \sin \frac{\theta}{2}
\end{gathered}
\]

yielding

\[
\lambda-\lambda_{0}= \pm \frac{2 n v}{c} \lambda \sin \frac{\theta}{2}
\]

When two phonons interact to form a third phonon, the conservation of wave vectors applies, meaning the total wave vector of the phonons before and after the interaction are equal. Therefore, the wave vector of the third phonon is:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{q}_{3} & =\boldsymbol{q}_{1}+\boldsymbol{q}_{2} \\
& =1.3 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{i}+0.92 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{i}+0.92 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{j} \\
& =2.22 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{i}+0.92 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^{-1} \, \boldsymbol{j}
\end{aligned}
\]

This indicates that the resulting wave vector falls outside the first Brillouin zone and needs to be adjusted through spatial periodicity.

Substituting \(\rho=3.79 \times 10^{-11} \, \text{m}=0.379 \, \text{Å}\) into

\[
\begin{aligned}
\lambda &= \frac{\rho M e^{2}}{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} r_{0}^{2}} e^{\frac{r_{0}}{\rho}} \\
&= \frac{3.79 \times 10^{-11} \times 1.7476 \times \left(1.602 \times 10^{-19}\right)^{2}}{4 \times 3.1416 \times 8.85 \times 10^{-12} \times \left(3.29 \times 10^{-10}\right)^{2}} e^{\frac{3.29 \times 10^{-10}}{3.79 \times 10^{-11}}} \\
&= 8.315 \times 10^{-16} \, \text{J}
\end{aligned}
\]

Since the restoring force decreases in proportion to the vacancy concentration, when there is a vacancy concentration of \(n\) in the crystal, the restoring force coefficients are

\[
\begin{aligned}
& c_{1}=c_{1}^{0}(1-B n), \\
& c_{2}=c_{2}^{0}(1-B n)
\end{aligned}
\]

where \(c_{1}^{0}, c_{2}^{0}\) are the restoring force constants for the complete crystal, and \(B\) is a proportional constant. By substituting into equation (2), the speed of sound is

\[
\begin{aligned}
v_{s} & =\frac{a}{2} \sqrt{\frac{\left(c_{1}^{0}\right)^{2}(1-B n)^{2} \sin ^{2}\left(q_{1} a\right)+\left(c_{2}^{0}\right)^{2}(1-B n)^{2} \sin ^{2}\left(q_{2} a\right)}{m c_{1}^{0}(1-B n)\left[1-\cos \left(q_{1} a\right)\right]+m c_{2}^{0}(1-B n)\left[1-\cos \left(q_{2} a\right)\right]}} \\
& \propto \sqrt{1-B n} \propto \sqrt{1-B^{\prime} \exp \left(-\frac{\varepsilon}{k_{B} T}\right)}
\end{aligned}
\]

The derivation in the above formula applies \(n \propto \mathrm{e}^{-\frac{\varepsilon}{k_{B} T}}\).

