Let the area of the two-dimensional close-packed structure be \(S\), and the number of atoms be \(N\). Each atom contributes one free electron, thus we have

\[
\begin{gathered}
2 \cdot \frac{S}{(2 \pi)^{2}} \cdot \pi k_{\mathrm{F}}^{2} = N \\
k_{\mathrm{F}}^{2} = 2 \pi \frac{N}{S}
\end{gathered}
\]

\(\frac{N}{S}\) is the number of atoms per unit area, which can be calculated as follows. Consider an equilateral triangle with side length \(a\), and all three angles equal to \(60^{\circ}\), so its area is

\[
\frac{1}{2} \times a \times a \times \sin 60^{\circ} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} a^{2}
\]

However, each atom at the vertices of the equilateral triangle only contributes \(\frac{1}{6}\) of an atom to the triangle, so one equilateral triangle contains only \(\frac{1}{2}\) of an atom

\[
\frac{N}{S} = \frac{\frac{1}{2}}{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} a^{2}} = \frac{2}{\sqrt{3} a^{2}}
\]

Thus the Fermi wave vector \(k_{\mathrm{F}}^{2} = 2 \pi \cdot \frac{2}{\sqrt{3} a^{2}}\), which means

\[
k_{\mathrm{F}} = \frac{2}{a}\left(\frac{\pi}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}
\]

